WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.730 --> 00:00:06.260
Prof: The subject of
today's lecture is hedging.

00:00:06.260 --> 00:00:09.760
So this is what hedge funds do.
 

00:00:09.760 --> 00:00:13.000
It's what almost everyone on
Wall Street does nowadays,

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:16.059
at least to some extent,
say half the people on Wall

00:00:16.059 --> 00:00:17.260
Street nowadays.
 

00:00:17.260 --> 00:00:20.750
It was hardly done at all in
the past.

00:00:20.750 --> 00:00:24.755
So first of all,
just to mention what a hedge

00:00:24.755 --> 00:00:29.580
fund is, a hedge fund is a firm
that manages money.

00:00:29.580 --> 00:00:32.110
And why is it different from
any other firm that manages

00:00:32.110 --> 00:00:32.479
money?
 

00:00:32.479 --> 00:00:35.320
Well, the definition of hedge
fund basically has three parts.

00:00:35.320 --> 00:00:38.120
One is that hedge funds hedge.
 

00:00:38.120 --> 00:00:41.840
Now I'll say what that is in a
second.

00:00:41.840 --> 00:00:46.490
Secondly, hedge funds use
borrowed money in addition to

00:00:46.490 --> 00:00:49.850
their investors' money to buy
assets.

00:00:49.850 --> 00:00:52.494
So they do what's called
leveraging, which is going to be

00:00:52.494 --> 00:00:55.470
an important subject for the
last few lectures of the course.

00:00:55.470 --> 00:00:58.381
And thirdly,
they charge their investors

00:00:58.381 --> 00:00:59.650
very high fees.
 

00:00:59.650 --> 00:01:01.469
That's basically the definition
of a hedge fund,

00:01:01.469 --> 00:01:03.369
because they're supposed to be
so good at what they do,

00:01:03.369 --> 00:01:07.129
they can charge high fees and
still get the investors.

00:01:07.129 --> 00:01:09.078
So what is hedging?
 

00:01:09.078 --> 00:01:14.846
Hedging is the idea that you
want to cancel out some of your

00:01:14.846 --> 00:01:15.629
risks.
 

00:01:15.629 --> 00:01:18.441
So for instance,
you might know that a company's

00:01:18.441 --> 00:01:21.495
not going to default,
whereas the rest of the market

00:01:21.495 --> 00:01:23.530
thinks it is going to default.
 

00:01:23.530 --> 00:01:27.114
So you know the company's worth
more than the rest of the market

00:01:27.114 --> 00:01:30.129
thinks, so you might be tempted
to buy the company.

00:01:30.129 --> 00:01:33.489
But if the interest rate were
to change,

00:01:33.489 --> 00:01:35.730
say go way up and the company's
paying,

00:01:35.730 --> 00:01:39.590
has constant cash payments,
if the interest rate goes way

00:01:39.590 --> 00:01:42.970
up and the company has constant
cash payments,

00:01:42.970 --> 00:01:45.280
you could end up losing money
anyway,

00:01:45.280 --> 00:01:47.340
because the present value's
going to go down,

00:01:47.340 --> 00:01:49.120
just because the interest rate
has gone up.

00:01:49.120 --> 00:01:51.819
So what a hedger would do is,
the hedger would say,

00:01:51.819 --> 00:01:56.405
"Look, I'm relying on my
expertise as an evaluator to

00:01:56.405 --> 00:01:59.140
realize there's no default risk.
 

00:01:59.140 --> 00:02:03.140
I want to bet that there's no
default risk in this company.

00:02:03.140 --> 00:02:04.120
It's not going to default.
 

00:02:04.120 --> 00:02:06.906
I don't want to bet on which
way interest rates are going to

00:02:06.906 --> 00:02:08.336
go,
because I don't know which way

00:02:08.336 --> 00:02:11.010
interest rates are going to go,
so I want to hedge myself

00:02:11.010 --> 00:02:12.139
against that."
 

00:02:12.139 --> 00:02:19.060
So to take-- sorry,
I'm just starting here.

00:02:19.060 --> 00:02:22.580
Hello.
 

00:02:22.580 --> 00:02:28.490
Sorry, hard to talk when
everyone else is talking.

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:30.750
So what does hedging a risk
means?

00:02:30.750 --> 00:02:33.494
It means no matter which way
the risk factor goes,

00:02:33.494 --> 00:02:36.910
you're going to still end up
with the same amount of money.

00:02:36.910 --> 00:02:41.573
So the first person to do this
and call himself a hedge fund

00:02:41.573 --> 00:02:46.473
was somebody named Jones in the
1940s and he was a stock picker

00:02:46.473 --> 00:02:50.979
who would try to find the best
possible stock to buy.

00:02:50.979 --> 00:02:52.601
So before him,
people would say,

00:02:52.601 --> 00:02:54.849
"Okay, Ford is a great
auto company.

00:02:54.849 --> 00:02:56.840
We're going to buy Ford."
 

00:02:56.840 --> 00:03:00.930
The trouble is that Ford may in
fact turn out to be the best

00:03:00.930 --> 00:03:03.907
auto company,
but because the whole economy

00:03:03.907 --> 00:03:06.491
collapsed,
it may be that Ford collapsed

00:03:06.491 --> 00:03:10.055
with the rest of the economy,
even though it did better than

00:03:10.055 --> 00:03:11.680
all the other auto companies.
 

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:13.959
So what Jones said is,
"I'm not going to just buy

00:03:13.959 --> 00:03:14.258
Ford.
 

00:03:14.258 --> 00:03:16.860
What I'm going to do is,
I'm going to buy Ford and I'm

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:19.921
going to sell General Motors,
so that way I'm going to be

00:03:19.921 --> 00:03:23.240
betting not on whether Ford is
better than General Motors,

00:03:23.240 --> 00:03:25.483
and in addition,
whether the whole economy's

00:03:25.483 --> 00:03:26.370
going to go up.
 

00:03:26.370 --> 00:03:29.114
I only want to bet on whether
Ford is better than General

00:03:29.114 --> 00:03:29.848
Motors."
 

00:03:29.848 --> 00:03:32.776
So if the whole economy goes
down, Ford and General Motors

00:03:32.776 --> 00:03:34.008
will go down together.
 

00:03:34.008 --> 00:03:37.263
So what you own in Ford,
you won't own something as

00:03:37.263 --> 00:03:40.144
valuable any more,
but what you owe by having sold

00:03:40.144 --> 00:03:42.490
General Motors short also won't
be as valuable.

00:03:42.490 --> 00:03:45.395
So what you've bought and what
you've sold will cancel each

00:03:45.395 --> 00:03:47.699
other out and you won't have
lost any money.

00:03:47.699 --> 00:03:50.129
On the other hand,
if Ford ends up doing better

00:03:50.129 --> 00:03:52.664
than General Motors,
you'll have gained more with

00:03:52.664 --> 00:03:55.360
Ford than you'll have lost with
General Motors.

00:03:55.360 --> 00:03:57.710
So whether the economy goes up
or down,

00:03:57.710 --> 00:04:00.788
if the gap between Ford and
General Motors stays the same,

00:04:00.788 --> 00:04:04.472
you won't lose or win money,
so you're hedged against

00:04:04.472 --> 00:04:06.810
general changes in the economy.
 

00:04:06.810 --> 00:04:09.455
You're only going to make or
lose money depending on the

00:04:09.455 --> 00:04:11.430
spread between Ford and General
Motors.

00:04:11.430 --> 00:04:13.996
So you've canceled out the
economy wide risk and you're

00:04:13.996 --> 00:04:16.324
only holding one risk,
which you really think that

00:04:16.324 --> 00:04:17.370
you've understood.
 

00:04:17.370 --> 00:04:20.209
So that's what hedging is.
 

00:04:20.209 --> 00:04:23.045
So I'm going to now show you
that hedging is actually a

00:04:23.045 --> 00:04:24.410
slightly delicate thing.
 

00:04:24.410 --> 00:04:30.372
It's quite complicated and
we're going to learn the

00:04:30.372 --> 00:04:34.069
technique of dynamic hedging.
 

00:04:34.069 --> 00:04:37.569
Now why is dynamic hedging so
important?

00:04:37.569 --> 00:04:41.041
Dynamic hedging is so important
because there are so many things

00:04:41.041 --> 00:04:43.492
that can happen in the future,
and as I said,

00:04:43.492 --> 00:04:45.209
for example,
if you hold a mortgage,

00:04:45.209 --> 00:04:47.339
you may think the mortgage is
more valuable,

00:04:47.339 --> 00:04:49.149
because you know people aren't
going to default,

00:04:49.149 --> 00:04:51.329
and the rest of the economy
thinks they're going to default.

00:04:51.329 --> 00:04:53.374
On the other hand,
the value of the mortgage will

00:04:53.374 --> 00:04:55.973
change with the interest rate,
so you want to protect yourself

00:04:55.973 --> 00:04:57.550
against the interest rate
change.

00:04:57.550 --> 00:05:01.019
But it's not just the
interest rate change.

00:05:01.019 --> 00:05:03.547
Over ten years or 30 years,
the life of the mortgage,

00:05:03.547 --> 00:05:06.610
there are going to be a huge
number of interest rate changes.

00:05:06.610 --> 00:05:09.235
There'll be a whole path of
interest rate changes,

00:05:09.235 --> 00:05:12.504
and the mortgage will be paying
different cash flows along the

00:05:12.504 --> 00:05:13.310
whole path.
 

00:05:13.310 --> 00:05:15.862
In over 30 years,
even if you think of only one

00:05:15.862 --> 00:05:18.233
change a day,
there's an exponentially

00:05:18.233 --> 00:05:20.939
growing set of changes,
so there's an exponential

00:05:20.939 --> 00:05:21.730
number of paths.
 

00:05:21.730 --> 00:05:24.935
You'll never be able to
equalize your cash flows,

00:05:24.935 --> 00:05:27.740
you would think,
over every single path.

00:05:27.740 --> 00:05:29.160
There are just too many of them.
 

00:05:29.160 --> 00:05:32.788
But dynamic hedging says you
don't have to equalize over

00:05:32.788 --> 00:05:35.230
every path from the very
beginning.

00:05:35.230 --> 00:05:37.959
That is, you don't have to hold
a portfolio at the very

00:05:37.959 --> 00:05:40.944
beginning that equalizes your
cash flows by the end of every

00:05:40.944 --> 00:05:41.399
path.
 

00:05:41.399 --> 00:05:45.255
You only have to equalize your
cash flow one step at a time and

00:05:45.255 --> 00:05:47.620
then dynamically change your
hedge,

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:50.656
so it's a much easier thing to
hedge than it sounds at first

00:05:50.656 --> 00:05:51.120
glance.
 

00:05:51.120 --> 00:05:53.423
So I want to illustrate that,
because you can't know what

00:05:53.423 --> 00:05:55.110
that means yet until we see an
example.

00:05:55.110 --> 00:05:57.889
So let's start with a very easy
thing to understand,

00:05:57.889 --> 00:06:00.290
the World Series,
where we started before.

00:06:00.290 --> 00:06:03.639
So you have some expertise,
in fact, there are other people

00:06:03.639 --> 00:06:07.278
besides you who have the same
expertise, these other bookies.

00:06:07.278 --> 00:06:10.235
You all know the Yankees have a
60 percent chance of winning

00:06:10.235 --> 00:06:13.117
every game against the Phillies,
and let's just assume for

00:06:13.117 --> 00:06:15.918
simplicity that the World Series
is only going to take a couple

00:06:15.918 --> 00:06:16.459
of weeks.
 

00:06:16.459 --> 00:06:19.290
The interest rate is 0 over
such a short period of time.

00:06:19.290 --> 00:06:22.983
You don't care whether you get
the money now or at the end of 2

00:06:22.983 --> 00:06:25.129
weeks, just so long as you get
it.

00:06:25.129 --> 00:06:29.310
You can borrow or lend at 0
interest over those short number

00:06:29.310 --> 00:06:30.019
of days.
 

00:06:30.019 --> 00:06:34.305
And secondly,
you know that the probability

00:06:34.305 --> 00:06:37.060
of winning is 60 percent.
 

00:06:37.060 --> 00:06:41.464
Now suppose that some naive
person comes to you and says,

00:06:41.464 --> 00:06:43.589
"I'm a Phillies fan.
 

00:06:43.589 --> 00:06:46.925
I want to bet at even odds that
the Phillies are going to win

00:06:46.925 --> 00:06:48.259
for 100 dollars."
 

00:06:48.259 --> 00:06:52.714
So you're going to now get a
payoff that's -100 dollars at

00:06:52.714 --> 00:06:56.310
the end of game 7,
assuming I counted right.

00:06:56.310 --> 00:06:58.290
So this is the start.
 

00:06:58.290 --> 00:07:03.887
This would be game 1 here,
so it's 1,2,

00:07:03.887 --> 00:07:05.949
3,4, 5,6, 7.
 

00:07:05.949 --> 00:07:10.399
So by the end of game 7,
if you played it to the end,

00:07:10.399 --> 00:07:13.898
you would have made 100 dollars
if the Yankees won a majority of

00:07:13.898 --> 00:07:16.603
the games,
and you'd have lost 100 dollars

00:07:16.603 --> 00:07:19.870
if the Yankees didn't win a
majority of the games.

00:07:19.870 --> 00:07:21.639
So how much is that worth to
you?

00:07:21.639 --> 00:07:25.649
Well obviously it's worth a lot
more than 20 dollars,

00:07:25.649 --> 00:07:28.175
because if they only played 1
game and the Yankees had a 60

00:07:28.175 --> 00:07:30.956
percent chance of winning,
the expected payoff for the

00:07:30.956 --> 00:07:34.634
Yankees,
that bet for 1 game would be 20

00:07:34.634 --> 00:07:38.545
dollars,
because you know in 1 game a .6

00:07:38.545 --> 00:07:42.389
chance of 100 and a .4 chance of
- 100,

00:07:42.389 --> 00:07:45.810
that gives you an expectation
of 20.

00:07:45.810 --> 00:07:47.480
60 - 40 is 20.
 

00:07:47.480 --> 00:07:49.370
However, we're playing a seven
game series.

00:07:49.370 --> 00:07:51.995
The whole point of playing a
long series is that the Yankees

00:07:51.995 --> 00:07:53.110
are more likely to win.
 

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:55.079
The better team is more likely
to win,

00:07:55.079 --> 00:07:57.264
and in fact,
we know that by doing this

00:07:57.264 --> 00:08:01.122
backward induction calculation,
we know that the expected

00:08:01.122 --> 00:08:04.170
winnings for the Yankees is 42
dollars.

00:08:04.170 --> 00:08:07.500
However, the Yankees--you could
lose 100 dollars.

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:10.223
If the Phillies just got lucky,
you could lose as well as win

00:08:10.223 --> 00:08:10.860
100 dollars.
 

00:08:10.860 --> 00:08:14.129
You don't want to face that
risk, so what could you do?

00:08:14.129 --> 00:08:19.547
Well, the simplest thing to do
is to go to another bookie and

00:08:19.547 --> 00:08:21.408
say,
"I want to bet on the

00:08:21.408 --> 00:08:23.490
World Series,"
with this other bookie.

00:08:23.490 --> 00:08:29.853
So if the bookie is willing to
make a bet with you for the

00:08:29.853 --> 00:08:33.333
whole series,
so the bookie has to be pretty

00:08:33.333 --> 00:08:35.820
sophisticated and do the same
calculation,

00:08:35.820 --> 00:08:41.424
the bookie is going to let you
bet however you want to at the

00:08:41.424 --> 00:08:42.639
right odds.
 

00:08:42.639 --> 00:08:46.659
So what would you do?
 

00:08:46.659 --> 00:08:47.850
So here you can win 100.
 

00:08:47.850 --> 00:08:49.558
There are only two outcomes.
 

00:08:49.558 --> 00:08:54.259
You can win 100 or you can lose
100.

00:08:54.259 --> 00:08:58.511
Now the odds of winning the
series, I forgot to say,

00:08:58.511 --> 00:09:00.929
we figured this out before.
 

00:09:00.929 --> 00:09:03.440
Oh dear, what were the odds?
 

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:08.149
Hope I have another one of
these World Series things.

00:09:08.149 --> 00:09:13.351
Okay, so what are the odds that
the Yankees are going to win the

00:09:13.351 --> 00:09:14.590
World Series?
 

00:09:14.590 --> 00:09:15.750
We calculated this before.
 

00:09:15.750 --> 00:09:19.360
Do you remember what it was?
 

00:09:19.360 --> 00:09:25.038
Well, we know some probability
P times 100 some probability (1

00:09:25.038 --> 00:09:27.460
- P), -100 gives you 42.
 

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:35.919
So P times 100 (1 - P) times -
100 = 42 approximately.

00:09:35.919 --> 00:09:37.320
That's 42, right?
 

00:09:37.320 --> 00:09:48.565
So we know that therefore,
2P times 100 = 142,

00:09:48.565 --> 00:10:02.058
so P = 142 over 100 times 2,
which equals about .71.

00:10:02.058 --> 00:10:04.904
Okay, so this other bookie
would have calculated the odds

00:10:04.904 --> 00:10:07.801
are 71 percent that the Yankees
are going to win the World

00:10:07.801 --> 00:10:08.360
Series.
 

00:10:08.360 --> 00:10:10.769
We calculated this a few
classes ago.

00:10:10.769 --> 00:10:14.018
The Yankees have a 71 percent
chance of winning the World

00:10:14.018 --> 00:10:14.538
Series.
 

00:10:14.538 --> 00:10:17.034
So if you went to another
bookie who could do this

00:10:17.034 --> 00:10:19.292
calculation,
the other bookie would be

00:10:19.292 --> 00:10:22.573
willing to give you odds of 71
percent Yankees versus 39

00:10:22.573 --> 00:10:24.423
percent [correction:
29 percent]

00:10:24.423 --> 00:10:26.855
Phillies,
so you could just unload this

00:10:26.855 --> 00:10:28.918
whole bet and get 42 dollars for
sure.

00:10:28.918 --> 00:10:35.110
In fact, what would you bet
with the other guy?

00:10:35.110 --> 00:10:38.870
What would you bet with the
other bookie?

00:10:38.870 --> 00:10:40.750
What would you do if you could
bet on the whole World Series?

00:10:40.750 --> 00:10:41.769
Somebody suggested that.
 

00:10:41.769 --> 00:10:43.908
He was sitting over there at
the end of the last class.

00:10:43.908 --> 00:10:46.908
What would you do if you could
bet on the whole World Series

00:10:46.908 --> 00:10:48.129
with the other bookie?
 

00:10:48.129 --> 00:10:49.500
What bet would you make?
 

00:10:49.500 --> 00:10:53.538
You know that the bet is giving
you 42 dollars on expectation.

00:10:53.538 --> 00:10:55.408
The trouble is,
some of the time it's giving

00:10:55.408 --> 00:10:57.539
you 100, some of the time it's
giving you -100.

00:10:57.539 --> 00:10:58.840
You don't want to fix this risk.
 

00:10:58.840 --> 00:11:01.980
You want to end up with 42
dollars for sure.

00:11:01.980 --> 00:11:09.000
Now how can you do that?
 

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.312
Well, if you did -68
[correction: -58]

00:11:13.312 --> 00:11:18.674
here, that would = 42,
and if you did 142 here,

00:11:18.674 --> 00:11:21.590
that would also = 42.
 

00:11:21.590 --> 00:11:25.667
So could you figure out a way
of betting with the other

00:11:25.667 --> 00:11:27.480
bookies 142 versus 58?
 

00:11:27.480 --> 00:11:32.197
You win 142 if the Phillies
win, and you lose 58 if the

00:11:32.197 --> 00:11:33.418
Yankees win?
 

00:11:33.418 --> 00:11:37.808
Student:
&gt;

00:11:37.808 --> 00:11:50.080
Prof: That's not 42 by
the way.

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:58.429
Okay, would another bookie be
willing to give you this bet?

00:11:58.429 --> 00:12:00.250
What's the answer?
 

00:12:00.250 --> 00:12:00.990
The answer is yes.
 

00:12:00.990 --> 00:12:11.471
How do you know the other
bookie would be willing to give

00:12:11.471 --> 00:12:14.278
you this bet?
 

00:12:14.278 --> 00:12:20.700
What is P times 42 (1 - P)
times 42?

00:12:20.700 --> 00:12:21.750
It's 42.
 

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:25.039
What's P times 100 (1 - P)
times -100.

00:12:25.039 --> 00:12:26.548
It's also 42.
 

00:12:26.548 --> 00:12:29.650
So therefore,
what's P times this (1 - P)

00:12:29.650 --> 00:12:30.659
times that?
 

00:12:30.659 --> 00:12:33.779
Student: 0.
 

00:12:33.779 --> 00:12:34.690
Prof: 0.
 

00:12:34.690 --> 00:12:37.047
So at the odds,
P and 1 - P,

00:12:37.047 --> 00:12:39.580
this bet is perfectly fair.
 

00:12:39.580 --> 00:12:41.986
So the other bookie would say
that's the odds,

00:12:41.986 --> 00:12:43.700
71 percent to 39 [29]
percent.

00:12:43.700 --> 00:12:46.190
That's exactly what these odds
are.

00:12:46.190 --> 00:12:49.472
So if P times this (1 - P)
times that is 42,

00:12:49.472 --> 00:12:53.748
and P times this (1 - P) times
that, that's obviously 42,

00:12:53.748 --> 00:12:57.490
must be P times this (1 - P)
times that is 0.

00:12:57.490 --> 00:12:59.190
In other words,
at the odds,

00:12:59.190 --> 00:13:01.140
P and 1 - P,
this is a fair bet,

00:13:01.140 --> 00:13:04.288
so the other bookie would give
you those odds.

00:13:04.288 --> 00:13:08.230
So that's what's hedging is in
its simplest form.

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:09.950
We haven't had to do anything
dynamic.

00:13:09.950 --> 00:13:12.984
Some guy is willing to bet on
the World Series with you,

00:13:12.984 --> 00:13:15.631
so you know that he's done
something wrong in his

00:13:15.631 --> 00:13:16.570
calculations.
 

00:13:16.570 --> 00:13:20.090
He's got the wrong P,
so you can take advantage of

00:13:20.090 --> 00:13:21.240
the situation.
 

00:13:21.240 --> 00:13:23.428
You know that P is higher than
he does.

00:13:23.428 --> 00:13:25.898
On the other hand,
there's still God in the

00:13:25.898 --> 00:13:28.806
background and luck,
which might make the Phillies

00:13:28.806 --> 00:13:32.080
win, and so you don't want to
subject yourself to that risk.

00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:33.340
So what do you do?
 

00:13:33.340 --> 00:13:36.558
You take the bet,
the advantageous bet,

00:13:36.558 --> 00:13:40.908
but you put together with the
advantageous bet a hedging bet,

00:13:40.908 --> 00:13:42.580
where you're betting on the
wrong team,

00:13:42.580 --> 00:13:44.210
the team you think is going to
lose.

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:45.720
But you're betting on the wrong
team,

00:13:45.720 --> 00:13:48.519
but this time,
at fair odds on the wrong team,

00:13:48.519 --> 00:13:51.450
and so you're transforming your
risky payoff,

00:13:51.450 --> 00:13:58.360
albeit with very favorable
odds--P we just said was .71--

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:02.701
you're taking your risky payoff
and turning it into a safe

00:14:02.701 --> 00:14:04.700
payoff of 42,
no matter what.

00:14:04.700 --> 00:14:06.629
That's the essence of hedging.
 

00:14:06.629 --> 00:14:09.197
In order to do that,
you might have to bet the

00:14:09.197 --> 00:14:12.110
opposite way that you think is
going to turn out.

00:14:12.110 --> 00:14:14.548
So there's principle number one.
 

00:14:14.548 --> 00:14:16.794
So let me pause and see if
there are any questions for

00:14:16.794 --> 00:14:17.600
that, about that.
 

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:21.830
The idea is that there's
something you know that you can

00:14:21.830 --> 00:14:25.368
take advantage of,
but life is more complicated

00:14:25.368 --> 00:14:28.830
than knowing one thing,
namely what P is.

00:14:28.830 --> 00:14:32.870
Life also involves all kinds of
other things that might happen.

00:14:32.870 --> 00:14:36.096
You want to insulate yourself
from those other things and

00:14:36.096 --> 00:14:39.438
concentrate entirely on what you
know about P and 1 - P and

00:14:39.438 --> 00:14:42.090
therefore assure yourself of a
bet of 42,

00:14:42.090 --> 00:14:43.558
no matter what.
 

00:14:43.558 --> 00:14:47.100
And you're taking advantage of
the fact that other people will

00:14:47.100 --> 00:14:49.190
also be able to bet at P with
you.

00:14:49.190 --> 00:14:51.860
This one outsider doesn't
understand that all the bookies

00:14:51.860 --> 00:14:54.673
are willing to take odds of P,
he's offering odds of 1 half,

00:14:54.673 --> 00:14:55.580
which is crazy.
 

00:14:55.580 --> 00:14:58.519
It's a big gap, 71,29 to P.
 

00:14:58.519 --> 00:15:03.730
So you can take 42 of his
dollars for sure.

00:15:03.730 --> 00:15:12.370
Okay, so now let's go to--okay,
this is hedging.

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:13.918
It's also an arbitrage.
 

00:15:13.918 --> 00:15:23.960
This is--hedging created a pure
arbitrage.

00:15:23.960 --> 00:15:27.102
In this case,
it's done even better than in

00:15:27.102 --> 00:15:30.626
my example with Ford,
because you've taken now a bet

00:15:30.626 --> 00:15:34.139
and transformed it with an
expectation you're going to win,

00:15:34.139 --> 00:15:39.200
into a bet where you can't
possibly lose.

00:15:39.200 --> 00:15:43.711
Okay, now suppose that these
other brokers weren't as clever

00:15:43.711 --> 00:15:44.399
as you.
 

00:15:44.399 --> 00:15:45.871
Suppose that the other
brokers--okay,

00:15:45.871 --> 00:15:46.690
so that's hedging.
 

00:15:46.690 --> 00:15:48.668
Now we're going to do dynamic
hedging.

00:15:48.668 --> 00:15:51.450
Suppose the other brokers,
they're not as smart as you.

00:15:51.450 --> 00:15:53.149
They don't know how to build
these trees.

00:15:53.149 --> 00:15:55.080
They can't do backward
induction.

00:15:55.080 --> 00:15:57.928
They just know the odds are 60
percent that the Yankees are

00:15:57.928 --> 00:16:00.139
going to win any game against
the Phillies.

00:16:00.139 --> 00:16:02.908
Now what would you do?
 

00:16:02.908 --> 00:16:04.798
Okay, you can't go to another
broker and say,

00:16:04.798 --> 00:16:07.158
"I want to bet on the
whole 7 game series."

00:16:07.158 --> 00:16:09.361
The guy's going to say,
"It's just too complicated

00:16:09.361 --> 00:16:09.730
for me.
 

00:16:09.730 --> 00:16:10.610
I'm a simple man.
 

00:16:10.610 --> 00:16:11.710
I make a simple living.
 

00:16:11.710 --> 00:16:14.038
I just do 1 game bets.
 

00:16:14.038 --> 00:16:17.190
I'll let you bet any game you
want.

00:16:17.190 --> 00:16:20.774
You tell me what you want to
bet, we'll bet one game at a

00:16:20.774 --> 00:16:21.990
time, 60/40 odds.
 

00:16:21.990 --> 00:16:24.283
The whole series,
it's much more complicated for

00:16:24.283 --> 00:16:24.820
me."
 

00:16:24.820 --> 00:16:29.000
So is there anything you can do
now?

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:31.690
What can you do now?
 

00:16:31.690 --> 00:16:36.313
So now you have to do something
more complicated,

00:16:36.313 --> 00:16:39.590
which is called dynamic
hedging.

00:16:39.590 --> 00:16:43.402
So we started to talk about
this last time,

00:16:43.402 --> 00:16:45.490
so what would you do?
 

00:16:45.490 --> 00:16:48.352
You only now have the
opportunity of protecting

00:16:48.352 --> 00:16:52.025
yourself against bad luck by
betting one game at a time with

00:16:52.025 --> 00:16:53.519
these other brokers.
 

00:16:53.519 --> 00:16:58.850
So what should you do?
 

00:16:58.850 --> 00:17:03.470
Well, let's look at this
picture here.

00:17:03.470 --> 00:17:08.001
You know that this bet of (
100, -100) by doing backward

00:17:08.001 --> 00:17:09.980
induction is worth 42.
 

00:17:09.980 --> 00:17:13.288
So if you were a trader,
a hedge fund manager,

00:17:13.288 --> 00:17:16.450
you would be marking your
position at 42.

00:17:16.450 --> 00:17:19.557
You're expecting now--you've
just made a trade which you know

00:17:19.557 --> 00:17:21.890
on average is going to make you
42 dollars.

00:17:21.890 --> 00:17:24.494
Of course, if you had bad luck,
you could end up losing 100

00:17:24.494 --> 00:17:26.333
dollars,
which means you're going to go

00:17:26.333 --> 00:17:28.061
out of business,
you're going to be fired,

00:17:28.061 --> 00:17:29.650
your name's going to be in the
newspaper,

00:17:29.650 --> 00:17:32.180
you're going to be probably
sued by your investors.

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:38.450
Or you can--we haven't been
sued by any investors.

00:17:38.450 --> 00:17:41.609
Or you might make 100 dollars.
 

00:17:41.609 --> 00:17:43.368
Now you don't want to face that.
 

00:17:43.368 --> 00:17:45.144
You want to hedge yourself,
protect yourself,

00:17:45.144 --> 00:17:46.960
so you're going to make the
money for sure.

00:17:46.960 --> 00:17:48.470
Now some people don't hedge.
 

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:51.482
They say when you hedge,
you're betting against

00:17:51.482 --> 00:17:54.170
yourself, and something bad can
happen.

00:17:54.170 --> 00:17:55.740
The hedge might go negative,
right?

00:17:55.740 --> 00:17:58.404
It may be that the Yankees win,
just as you think,

00:17:58.404 --> 00:18:01.287
but because you've hedged,
you're not going to get 100

00:18:01.287 --> 00:18:01.940
dollars.
 

00:18:01.940 --> 00:18:03.828
You're only going to get 42
dollars.

00:18:03.828 --> 00:18:06.938
So the essence of hedging is
you give something up on the

00:18:06.938 --> 00:18:09.269
upside to get something on the
downside.

00:18:09.269 --> 00:18:13.173
So people don't like hedging
because they're giving something

00:18:13.173 --> 00:18:13.500
up.
 

00:18:13.500 --> 00:18:14.759
Okay, so you're giving
something up.

00:18:14.759 --> 00:18:16.429
The point is,
you're getting something back

00:18:16.429 --> 00:18:18.257
on the downside,
and you're making it so you're

00:18:18.257 --> 00:18:19.329
locking in your profit.
 

00:18:19.329 --> 00:18:21.910
So hedging is a good thing.
 

00:18:21.910 --> 00:18:24.967
So people who don't hedge I
think they're just very simple

00:18:24.967 --> 00:18:25.450
minded.
 

00:18:25.450 --> 00:18:27.170
So there are a lot of people
who still don't hedge,

00:18:27.170 --> 00:18:30.001
but anyway, there's a
revolution in financial thought

00:18:30.001 --> 00:18:32.388
in the last 30 years,
anticipated by Ford

00:18:32.388 --> 00:18:34.721
[correction: Jones],
but it didn't really

00:18:34.721 --> 00:18:37.804
get--people didn't really catch
on until the '70s that you

00:18:37.804 --> 00:18:38.670
should hedge.
 

00:18:38.670 --> 00:18:42.141
So how can you hedge this if
you can only bet 1 time,

00:18:42.141 --> 00:18:43.410
1 game at a time?
 

00:18:43.410 --> 00:18:45.180
That was the question we dealt
with last time.

00:18:45.180 --> 00:18:47.450
What should you do?
 

00:18:47.450 --> 00:18:52.002
Well, you see the principles
we've learned so far tell us

00:18:52.002 --> 00:18:53.058
what to do.
 

00:18:53.058 --> 00:18:56.403
You started here thinking on
average you're going to make 42

00:18:56.403 --> 00:18:56.970
dollars.
 

00:18:56.970 --> 00:19:00.638
You should be marking your
position correctly that it's

00:19:00.638 --> 00:19:01.930
worth 42 dollars.
 

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:05.660
Now if you win the first game,
you're at a big advantage.

00:19:05.660 --> 00:19:09.915
The Yankees are up a game and
by backward induction we know

00:19:09.915 --> 00:19:13.660
that then your position will be
worth 64 dollars.

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:16.554
If you lose,
your position will be worth 8

00:19:16.554 --> 00:19:18.390
[correction: 9]
dollars.

00:19:18.390 --> 00:19:25.309
Now what is 60 percent of 64
plus 40 percent of 9?

00:19:25.309 --> 00:19:26.670
It's 42.
 

00:19:26.670 --> 00:19:32.740
60 percent of 64 is 38.4.
 

00:19:32.740 --> 00:19:38.138
So you're at 42 and you could
go with 60 percent probability

00:19:38.138 --> 00:19:42.165
to 60-- I can't even remember
the number--64,

00:19:42.165 --> 00:19:44.818
or down to .9,40 percent.
 

00:19:44.818 --> 00:19:49.210
Sorry, I'm getting senile,
9 with 40 percent probability.

00:19:49.210 --> 00:19:58.575
So 60 percent times that is
38.4 40 percent of 9 is 3.6 and

00:19:58.575 --> 00:20:02.288
the two add up to 42.
 

00:20:02.288 --> 00:20:05.259
So that's why--so to say the
value's worth 42,

00:20:05.259 --> 00:20:06.910
how did you get the 42?
 

00:20:06.910 --> 00:20:08.470
We were doing backward
induction.

00:20:08.470 --> 00:20:12.960
We took 60 percent of that 40
percent of that and we got 42.

00:20:12.960 --> 00:20:14.930
So if you're marking yourself
to market,

00:20:14.930 --> 00:20:16.730
after the first game of the
series,

00:20:16.730 --> 00:20:20.506
you'll have to admit to the
world that you're either now

00:20:20.506 --> 00:20:22.922
worth 64 dollars,
or you've gotten crushed,

00:20:22.922 --> 00:20:24.381
and you're down to 8
[correction: 9]

00:20:24.381 --> 00:20:24.838
dollars.
 

00:20:24.838 --> 00:20:27.028
That already might get you
fired.

00:20:27.028 --> 00:20:29.607
Going from 42 to 8 [correction:
9], that's a pretty drastic

00:20:29.607 --> 00:20:29.920
loss.
 

00:20:29.920 --> 00:20:34.529
So even the first day,
if you have to mark to market,

00:20:34.529 --> 00:20:36.678
you're going to be revealing to
the world that you've screwed up

00:20:36.678 --> 00:20:38.348
and now your position's only 8
[correction: 9].

00:20:38.348 --> 00:20:40.708
You've told all your investors,
you've done this brilliant

00:20:40.708 --> 00:20:41.039
thing.
 

00:20:41.039 --> 00:20:42.618
They're up 42 dollars.
 

00:20:42.618 --> 00:20:43.711
The next day,
you're going to have to tell

00:20:43.711 --> 00:20:44.884
them, "Well,
I'm sorry, you're only up 8

00:20:44.884 --> 00:20:45.789
[correction: 9]
dollars."

00:20:45.789 --> 00:20:47.430
They're going to be very upset.
 

00:20:47.430 --> 00:20:56.680
So what would you do?
 

00:20:56.680 --> 00:20:57.420
You know what to do.
 

00:20:57.420 --> 00:20:58.660
What would you do?
 

00:20:58.660 --> 00:21:02.599
Student: Hedge.
 

00:21:02.599 --> 00:21:03.250
Prof: Hedge.
 

00:21:03.250 --> 00:21:05.380
Good answer.
 

00:21:05.380 --> 00:21:06.500
How would you hedge?
 

00:21:06.500 --> 00:21:12.269
Student:
&gt;

00:21:12.269 --> 00:21:17.250
Prof: Right.
 

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:21.740
So what do you say?
 

00:21:21.740 --> 00:21:28.480
This is 9, so you'd go ( 33,
-22).

00:21:28.480 --> 00:21:32.430
So that's equal to 42 and
that's also equal to 42.

00:21:32.430 --> 00:21:34.019
Can you do this?
 

00:21:34.019 --> 00:21:36.470
Is it fair odds to do this?
 

00:21:36.470 --> 00:21:39.682
Well, yes, it has to be fair
odds to do this,

00:21:39.682 --> 00:21:43.769
because 60 percent of 64 40
percent of 9 is indeed 42.

00:21:43.769 --> 00:21:48.470
60 percent of 42 40 percent of
42 obviously is 42.

00:21:48.470 --> 00:21:51.166
So therefore the difference,
60 percent of this 40 percent

00:21:51.166 --> 00:21:52.869
of that must be 0,
so in other words,

00:21:52.869 --> 00:21:53.769
it's fair odds.
 

00:21:53.769 --> 00:21:56.597
And sure enough,
this is obviously 3 to 2 odds,

00:21:56.597 --> 00:21:57.088
right?
 

00:21:57.088 --> 00:21:59.150
60/40 means you're betting at 3
to 2 odds.

00:21:59.150 --> 00:22:00.380
That's 3 to 2 odds.
 

00:22:00.380 --> 00:22:02.487
So it is a fair bet,
so the other bookie who's

00:22:02.487 --> 00:22:05.390
willing to bet at 3 to 2 odds is
going to give you this bet.

00:22:05.390 --> 00:22:08.261
So again, you think the Yankees
are going to win,

00:22:08.261 --> 00:22:11.794
you make a bet with the naive
Philly fan, you're betting the

00:22:11.794 --> 00:22:13.528
Yankees are going to win.
 

00:22:13.528 --> 00:22:18.770
You go to your broker friend
and you bet against your

00:22:18.770 --> 00:22:19.778
Yankees.
 

00:22:19.778 --> 00:22:23.201
You're going to lose 22 dollars
if the Yankees win,

00:22:23.201 --> 00:22:25.460
and win 33 if the Phillies win.
 

00:22:25.460 --> 00:22:28.099
You're betting against
yourself, but of course you're

00:22:28.099 --> 00:22:30.892
betting against yourself to a
smaller extent than you're

00:22:30.892 --> 00:22:36.103
betting against the other guy,
and therefore you still locked

00:22:36.103 --> 00:22:37.818
in 42 dollars.
 

00:22:37.818 --> 00:22:40.538
So now we don't have to go any
further.

00:22:40.538 --> 00:22:43.019
It would only be confusing to
go further.

00:22:43.019 --> 00:22:45.412
I usually go further,
so it would just be

00:22:45.412 --> 00:22:46.250
complicated.
 

00:22:46.250 --> 00:22:49.420
If you can do something once,
you can do it many times.

00:22:49.420 --> 00:22:56.844
So by making the right hedging
bet, you can lock in a profit up

00:22:56.844 --> 00:22:59.118
here and up here.
 

00:22:59.118 --> 00:23:03.868
But that means you can lock it
in going forward to the very

00:23:03.868 --> 00:23:08.290
end, because you can keep
repeating that hedge over and

00:23:08.290 --> 00:23:09.519
over again.
 

00:23:09.519 --> 00:23:11.730
Maybe I'd better go one step
further.

00:23:11.730 --> 00:23:13.640
You don't really believe me.
 

00:23:13.640 --> 00:23:16.368
So what could you do going from
here to here?

00:23:16.368 --> 00:23:22.528
Well, the average of here and
here is about 9.

00:23:22.528 --> 00:23:25.808
You've collected 33 dollars,
don't forget,

00:23:25.808 --> 00:23:27.730
from your hedging bet.
 

00:23:27.730 --> 00:23:30.807
So although this says 9,
you've got the 33 in the

00:23:30.807 --> 00:23:32.410
background, so it's 42.
 

00:23:32.410 --> 00:23:33.460
But it's 9.
 

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:36.092
So what you want to do,
this is 9, you just want to

00:23:36.092 --> 00:23:37.828
transform this and this into 9.
 

00:23:37.828 --> 00:23:40.690
Once you've transformed this
and this into 9,

00:23:40.690 --> 00:23:45.518
which you can do because 60
percent of this 40 percent of

00:23:45.518 --> 00:23:48.800
that is 9,
so the other broker--you can do

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:53.056
an offloading hedging bet with
another broker at 60/40 odds to

00:23:53.056 --> 00:23:54.660
get 9 for sure here.
 

00:23:54.660 --> 00:23:55.420
Why is that?
 

00:23:55.420 --> 00:23:58.490
Because 60 percent of this 40
percent of that is 9,

00:23:58.490 --> 00:24:00.480
so therefore there must be
offsetting--

00:24:00.480 --> 00:24:04.720
a bet he'd take that gave you 9
for sure in both cases,

00:24:04.720 --> 00:24:07.640
because the offsetting bet
would also be valued at 0

00:24:07.640 --> 00:24:09.130
according to 60/40 odds.
 

00:24:09.130 --> 00:24:13.406
So you can transform this and
this into 9s but don't forget,

00:24:13.406 --> 00:24:17.538
you've been paid the 33,
so actually this is 42 and 42.

00:24:17.538 --> 00:24:21.101
So you can keep 42 and 42 going
forever and by the end,

00:24:21.101 --> 00:24:22.750
you'll have 42 forever.
 

00:24:22.750 --> 00:24:24.240
So that's what dynamic hedging
is.

00:24:24.240 --> 00:24:26.190
It's as simple as that.
 

00:24:26.190 --> 00:24:27.390
Yes.
 

00:24:27.390 --> 00:24:28.800
Student:
In order to make money with

00:24:28.800 --> 00:24:30.650
hedging, wouldn't you have to
have someone who would bet

00:24:30.650 --> 00:24:31.859
against you with different odds?
 

00:24:31.859 --> 00:24:32.298
Prof: Yes.
 

00:24:32.298 --> 00:24:37.318
So how do you make money in
hedging?

00:24:37.318 --> 00:24:43.362
You effectively were betting
against the Phillies fan at 50

00:24:43.362 --> 00:24:45.999
percent odds,
and you've got your broker

00:24:45.999 --> 00:24:47.640
who's willing to give you 60
percent odds,

00:24:47.640 --> 00:24:49.450
and you're exploiting that gap.
 

00:24:49.450 --> 00:24:56.598
So let's do another--excellent
question you're asking.

00:24:56.598 --> 00:24:58.200
I haven't answered his question
yet.

00:24:58.200 --> 00:25:00.288
I want to give another example
to answer his question.

00:25:00.288 --> 00:25:02.950
What is really going on with
the hedging?

00:25:02.950 --> 00:25:05.038
What am I relying on?
 

00:25:05.038 --> 00:25:07.289
How many brokers do I have to
deal with to hedge?

00:25:07.289 --> 00:25:08.509
What's going on here?
 

00:25:08.509 --> 00:25:12.307
I've given an example of a
World Series where it's very

00:25:12.307 --> 00:25:14.700
simple to figure out what to do.
 

00:25:14.700 --> 00:25:33.250
So now I want to give an
example of a bond.

